CS542 Common Task¶

Dylan Tamayo¶

Week 1: Manual Prediction¶

Temperature forecasts from four sources were used to make manual predictions for each city:

  • Apple Weather app
  • Google Weather forecast (ex. https://www.google.com/search?q=weather+belvedere+castle)
  • The Weather Channel (https://www.weather.com)
  • Accuweather (https://www.accuweather.com/)

Forecasted maximum temperature from each source for each city was recorded around 10 AM; forecasted temperatures were then averaged and rounded to the nearest integer to determine the corresponding Kalshi market.

Week 2: Data Collection and Model Training¶

Data Collection¶

A total of six sources were used for each city through API calls, Python modules, and web scraping. A total of six sources were used for each city through API calls, Python modules, and web scraping. Sources provided data for historical weather data from 2019 until present day, the recent climatological reports from the National Weather Service, or forecasts for upcoming days. Packages and version information are included in cs542_task.yml.

Data collection is as follows:

  • On a given day (ex. 3/25/2024), historical data was retrieved from five years (3/25/2019) until the day prior (3/24/2024).
  • The recent climatological reports which determine Kalshi market outcomes were scraped from the NWS website.
  • Forecasts for upcoming days were retrieved. Files for each source are saved in that day's directory (2024.03.25) for each city.

To combine all six sources into one dataset consisting of date and maximum temperature, dates were adjusted into YYYY-MM-DD format, and then temperatures were averaged across dates for all sources.

Model Training¶

Several machine learning models were tested to forecast weather, including transformers, RNN, linear regression, random forest and gradient boosting regression algorithm.

Attempted manipulations of the data included predicting on year, month, and date as separate features instead of one feature, as well as removing the forecasted temperature of the predicted day from the dataset.

Ultimately, gradient boosting was used to predict weather, providing a balance between low MSE, computational resource usage, and accuracy to other weather forecasts. Forecasts were made using year, month, and date as separate input features, with no other manipulations to the data.

Week 3: Automated Prediction¶

Using the Kalshi API starter code, the appropriate market was selected according to the predicted forecast for each city. One Yes contract with a limit price of $0.99 was selected and set to expire at market close.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from matplotlib.dates import DateFormatter, MonthLocator

path = os.getcwd()

# Convert the 'Prediction Date' column to datetime format
df['Prediction Date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Prediction Date'])

# Plot Prediction vs Historical for each city
cities = ['New York', 'Austin', 'Chicago', 'Miami']
for city in cities:
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    plt.plot(df['Prediction Date'], df[f'{city}_Historical'], label=f'{city} Historical', color='gray', alpha=0.7)
    plt.plot(df['Prediction Date'], df[f'{city}_Prediction'], label=f'{city} Prediction', color='red', alpha=0.7)
    plt.xlabel('Date')
    plt.ylabel('Value')
    plt.title(f'{city} Prediction vs Historical')
    plt.legend()

    plt.xticks(rotation=45)

    plt.show()

from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
from math import sqrt

cities = ['New York', 'Austin', 'Chicago', 'Miami']

# Calculate temp range for each city
print('City Maximum Temperature Range')
for city in cities:
    min_temp = df[f'{city}_Historical'].min()
    max_temp = df[f'{city}_Historical'].max()
    temp_range = max_temp - min_temp
    print(f'{city} - Min Temp: {min_temp}, Max Temp: {max_temp}, Temp Range: {temp_range}')
print()

# Calculate MSE and RMSE for each city
print('Historical vs. Predicted Error')
for city in cities:
    mse = mean_squared_error(df[f'{city}_Historical'], df[f'{city}_Prediction'])
    rmse = sqrt(mse)
    print(f'{city} - MSE: {round(mse, 3)}, RMSE: {round(rmse, 3)}')

import numpy as np 
from sklearn.metrics import r2_score

cities = ['New York', 'Austin', 'Chicago', 'Miami']
temp_range = [79, 85, 100, 47]
mse = [49.055, 57.034, 75.997, 12.279]
rmse = [7.004, 7.552, 8.718, 3.504]

# Sort lists by temp_range
temp_range_sorted, mse_sorted, rmse_sorted, cities_sorted = zip(*sorted(zip(temp_range, mse, rmse, cities)))

# Calculate R-squared values for linearity
def calculate_r2_linearity(x, y):
    slope, intercept = np.polyfit(x, y, 1)
    y_pred = slope * np.array(x) + intercept
    r2 = r2_score(y, y_pred)
    return r2

r2_mse_sorted = calculate_r2_linearity(temp_range_sorted, mse_sorted)
r2_rmse_sorted = calculate_r2_linearity(temp_range_sorted, rmse_sorted)

# Plot MSE and RMSE vs Temp Range
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))

plt.scatter(temp_range_sorted, mse_sorted, color='blue', label=f'MSE (R^2 = {r2_mse_sorted:.2f})')
plt.plot(temp_range_sorted, mse_sorted, color='blue', linestyle='--')

plt.scatter(temp_range_sorted, rmse_sorted, color='green', label=f'RMSE (R^2 = {r2_rmse_sorted:.2f})')
plt.plot(temp_range_sorted, rmse_sorted, color='green', linestyle='--')

# Annotate points with city labels
for i, city in enumerate(cities_sorted):
    plt.annotate(city, (temp_range_sorted[i], mse_sorted[i]), textcoords='offset points', xytext=(0,5), ha='center')
    plt.annotate(city, (temp_range_sorted[i], rmse_sorted[i]), textcoords='offset points', xytext=(0,5), ha='center')

plt.xlabel('Maximum Temperature Range')
plt.ylabel('Error')
plt.title('Range of Maximum Temperature vs Predicted Error')
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Historical data was averaged from the Open-Meteo and MeteoStat datasets for each city and rounded to the nearest integer. Plotting the historical data with the temperature predicted by gradient boosting, the predicted temperatures follow the cyclical seasonal weather patterns for each city. However, it appears that predictions are occasionally skewed by strong outliers, such as winter storms. Examples include Austin in 11/2022 and Miami in 12/2022.

The maximum temperature range for each city, taken as an indicator of temperature variability, scales linearly with the error MSE for each city. Based off these results, it is predicted that the gradient boosting model will perform the worst when predicting temperature for Chicago, and the best when predicting for Miami.

# Load the CSV file
path = os.getcwd()
df = pd.read_csv(f'{path}/common_task_results.csv')

# Group data by week
grouped = df.groupby('Week')

# Plot Predicted vs Actual MSE and RMSE for each city grouped by week
cities = ['New York', 'Austin', 'Chicago', 'Miami']
for week, group_data in grouped:
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(nrows=2, ncols=len(cities), figsize=(15, 8), sharex=True)

    for idx, city in enumerate(cities):
        city_data = group_data[group_data['City'] == city]

        # Plot Predicted vs Actual
        axs[0, idx].plot(city_data['Date'], city_data['Predicted'], marker='o', linestyle='-', color='red', label='Predicted')
        axs[0, idx].plot(city_data['Date'], city_data['Actual'], marker='o', linestyle='-', color='gray', label='Actual')
        axs[0, idx].set_title(f'{city} Predicted vs Actual')
        axs[0, idx].set_ylabel('Value')
        axs[0, idx].legend()
        axs[0, idx].grid(True)

        # Plot MSE and RMSE
        axs[1, idx].plot(city_data['Date'], city_data['MSE'], marker='o', linestyle='-', label='MSE')
        axs[1, idx].plot(city_data['Date'], city_data['RMSE'], marker='o', linestyle='-', label='RMSE')
        axs[1, idx].set_title(f'{city} MSE and RMSE')
        axs[1, idx].set_xlabel('Date')
        axs[1, idx].set_ylabel('Error')
        axs[1, idx].legend()
        axs[1, idx].grid(True)

    plt.suptitle(f'Week {week}')
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Comparing the results of Weeks 2 and 3 with Week 1, the gradient boosting model fared worse than predictions based off actual weather forecasts. As anticipated, Chicago had the highest error values, being on average 9.8 degrees off from the actual temperature for Week 2 and 5.8 degrees for Week 3.

In contrast to the predicted historical data, however, temperature predictions for New York outperformed Miami in Week 3.

Conclusions¶

Given the variability and randomness of day-to-day weather, predicting the forecast with perfect accuracy is an unlikely task. However, it is possible to achieve close results, as demonstrated by the forecast predictions used in Week 1 matching the trend of the actual weather. While the gradient boosted model achieved some accurate predictions, trends as predicted by the model often did not match actual. Extending the performance of the model beyond the two five-day periods of Weeks 2 and 3, would likely provide results that vary as heavily as the weather does.

Possible future directions for adjusting the model include:

  • Increasing or decreasing the amount of historical data used
  • Combining datasets for each city into one
  • Weighting recent days more heavily for forecasting weather
  • Adding features that may contribute to the maximum temperature such as humidity, precipitation, wind speed, daytime length

Alternative machine learning models such as transformers and RNNs may perform better than gradient boosting if additional features are added, if they are better able to identify more complex relationships.
